(Suzuki et al., 1993; Yokota, 1997) (Fig. 1).

Besides CR (
3
), cholesterol (CHR), 24-methylene-CHR (24-MCHR) (
1
), isofucosterol (IFUR), and sitosterol (STR) (
7
) are quite common in plants (Carland et al., 2002; Diener et al., 2000; Jang et al., 2000; Klahre et al., 1998; Schrick et al., 2000; Souter et al., 2002). Since 28-norCS, dolichosterone (DS) (
2
), 28-homodolichosterone, and 28-homocastasterone (28-homoCS) (
10
) have the same carbon backbone as CHR, 24-MCHR (
1
), IFUR, and STR (
7
), respectively, multiple biosynthetic pathways used to generate diverse BRs are operating in plants (Yokota, 1997). Recently, it was demonstrated in tomato and 
Arabidopsis
that 28-norCS is converted to CS (
6
) via DS (
2
), suggesting that the biosynthesis of 28-norCS from CHR and DS (
2
) from 24-MCHR (
1
) are alternative routes used to produce CS (
6
) in plants (Joo et al., 2012; Kim et al., 2004a).

From rice plants, the presence of 6-deoxocastasterone (6-deoxoCS), CS (
6
), BL, DS (
2
), 28-homoteasterone (28-homoTE) (
8
), and 28-homotyphasterol (28-homoTY) (
9
) was demonstrated (Bajguz and Tretyn, 2003). This implies that at least three biosynthetic pathways are operative to generate 24-methyl BRs [6-deoxoCS, CS

(
6
), and BL], 24-methylene BR [DS (
2
)], and 24-ethyl BRs [28-homoTE (
8
) and 28-homoTY (
9
)] in the rice plant. Hong et al. (2005) have reported that a defect in BR-deficient dwarf2 (
brd2
) increases endogenous levels of DS (
2
), but reduces the endogenous levels of CS (
6
) in rice. Recently, it was found that a 
BRD2
ortholog in 

Arabidopsis, 
DWARF

1, encodes a BR 24-reductase that catalyzes the conversion of DS (
2
) to CS (
6
) (unpublished data). These demonstrate that the biosynthesis of DS (
2
) is an alternative route to generate CS (
6
) in rice plants. However, the purpose of biosynthesis of 24-ethyl BRs occurs in rice has not been elucidated.

