2.1. Identification of 28-homoCS (
10
) from young seedlings of rice

document.paragraph:
The operation of C 
29
-BR biosynthesis in the rice seedlings was examined with a cell-free enzyme extract prepared from the seedlings. Prior to the enzyme assay, the presence of CS (
6
), which is the most abundant BR in rice seedlings, was investigated in the enzyme extract. CS (
6
) was not detected in the enzyme extract by GC–MS/SIM analysis, indicating that no detectable amounts of BRs were present in. C 
29
-BRs identified from rice plants such as 28-homoTE (
8
), 28-homoTY (
9
), and 28-homoCS (
10
) were incubated in the enzyme extract. After the enzyme assays, the products were purified by reversed-phase HPLC and analyzed by capillary GC–MS/SIM.

When 28-homoTE (
8
) was added to the enzyme extract as substrate, the methaneboronate-trimethylsilyl (MB-TMSi) ether from a compound in HPLC fractions 41 and 42 gave an identical mass spectrum and GC retention time as synthetic 28-homoTY (
9
) MB-TMSi (Table 2), demonstrating that 28-homoTE (
8
) was converted to 28-homoTY (
9
).The MB-TMSi ether derivatives for two other products in HPLC fractions 32 and 33 showed the same mass spectra as authentic TE (
4
) MB-TMSi. The GC retention time of 31.03 min for the MB-TMSi ether of one of the products was identical to that of authentic TE (
4
) MB-TMSi, demonstrating that the product is TE (
4
). Specific enzyme activity for conversion of 28-homoTE (
8
) to TE (
4
) was 1.18 ng mg protein 

