The occurrence of 28-homoCS (
10
) and its biosynthetic precursors, 28-homoTE (
8
) and 28-homoTY (
9
) was demonstrated in two monocots (

Oryza sativa

and 

Secale cereale

), three dicots (

Brassica campestris

, 

Raphanus sativus

, and 

Thea sinensis

), a gymnosperm (

Cupressus arizonica

), and an alga (

Hydrodictyon reticulatum

), indicating that C 
29
24-ethyl BRs are quite common in the plant kingdom (Abe et al., 1983, 1984, 1995; Griffiths et al., 1995; Schmidt et al., 1993, 1995; Yokota et al., 1987). Nevertheless, little is known about how C 
29
-BRs are biosynthesized in plants. In this study, 28- homoCS (
10
) from the seedlings of rice was identified. Coupled with the presence of STR (
7
), 28-homoTE (
8
), and 28-homoTY (
9
), this implies that 28-homoCS (
10
) can be biosynthesized from STR (
7
) via 28-homoTE (
8
) and 28-homoTY (
9
) in rice plants (Fig. 1). The enzyme extract prepared from the rice seedlings catalyzed the conversion of 28-homoTE (
8
) to 28-homoCS (
10
) via 28-homoTY (
9
). The C-3 epimerization, followed by C-2Oi hydroxyl-

