8
) has not been determined, these data suggest that 28-homoCS (
10
) is biosynthesized from STR (
7
) via a similar route to that of CS (
6
) from CR (
3
) and 28-norCS from CHR in plants.

In every plant where 28-homoCS (
10
) was identified, CS (
6
) always co-exists, suggesting that their biosynthesis are simultaneously operative and can be connected in the plants (Bajguz and Tretyn, 2003). In fact, in this study, the enzyme extract prepared from rice seedlings catalyzes conversion of 28-homoCS (
10
) to CS (
6
). Additionally, two biosynthetic precursors of 28-homoCS (
10
), 28-homoTE (
8
), and 28-homoTY (
9
), are converted into TE (
4
) and TY (
5
), respectively, demonstrating that C 
29
-BRs biosynthesis is biosynthetically connected to C 
28
-BRs biosynthesis between 28- homoTE (
8
) and TE (
4
), 28-homoTY (
9
) and TY (
5
), and 28-homoCS (
10
) and CS (
6
) in rice seedlings. The conversion rate in the rice enzyme solution for 28-homoTE (
8
) to TE (
4
), 28-homoTY (
9
) to TY (
5
), and 28-homoCS (
10
) to CS (
6
) indicates that the C-28 demethylase responsible for the conversion of C 
29
-BRs to C 
28
-BRs has a higher affinity for 28-homoCS (
10
) than for its biosynthetic precursors (Table 3). Therefore, it seems that the biosynthetic connection of C 
29
-BRs and C 
28
-BRs occurs mainly between the end products of the C 
29
-BR and C 
28
-BR pathways. Additionally, 28-homoTE (
8
), 28-homoTY (
9
), and 28-homoCS (
10
) show weak biological activity when compared to TE (
4
), TY (
5
), and CS (
6
), respectively, in the rice lamina inclination assay (Fig. 3), indicating that C-28 demethylation of 28-homoTE (
8
), 28-homoTY (
9
), and 28-homoCS (
10
) is a biosynthetic reaction which increases biological activity in BR biosynthesis. Together with the biosynthetic sequence TE (
4
) 
+
TY (
5
) 
+
CS (
6
), the biosynthesis of 24-ethyl BRs may thus be another route to produce the biologically active BR, CS (
6
), in the rice plants.

Before GC–MS/SIM analysis, the samples were subjected to methaneboronation and/or trimethylsilylation according to the structures of the expected metabolites. Methaneboronation was conducted by heating the samples dissolved in pyridine containing methanboronic acid (2 mg ml
– 1
) at 80 °C for 30 min. Trimethylsilylation was performed by addition of N -methyl- N -TMS-trifluoroacetamide (5 µl, MSTFA, Pierce, Rockford, IL) to the samples and heating at 80 °C for 30 min.
